00:00:33.450 --> 00:00:36.490 align:middle line:84%
>>And now the host of the
nationally syndicated Coast

00:00:36.490 --> 00:00:40.130 align:middle line:84%
to Coast AM and Gaiam TV
bring you "Beyond Belief"

00:00:40.130 --> 00:00:41.146 align:middle line:90%
with George Noory.

00:00:41.146 --> 00:00:42.720 align:middle line:90%
>> GEORGE NOORY: Well, hello.

00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:43.580 align:middle line:90%
Good to see you.

00:00:43.580 --> 00:00:45.205 align:middle line:90%
Welcome to "Beyond Belief."

00:00:45.205 --> 00:00:48.980 align:middle line:84%
You know, the mind is
an incredible apparatus.

00:00:48.980 --> 00:00:52.740 align:middle line:84%
It can be trained to do some
truly remarkable things.

00:00:52.740 --> 00:00:55.290 align:middle line:84%
But as you will find
out, it can also

00:00:55.290 --> 00:00:58.890 align:middle line:84%
be trained to do some very
horrible, dark things.

00:00:58.890 --> 00:01:01.380 align:middle line:84%
Our guest today
on "Beyond Belief"

00:01:01.380 --> 00:01:05.250 align:middle line:84%
is the son of the late
congressman Nick Begich, Sr.

00:01:05.250 --> 00:01:08.550 align:middle line:84%
He's a noted author, "Angels
Don't Play This HAARP."

00:01:08.550 --> 00:01:10.310 align:middle line:90%
Please welcome Nick Begich.

00:01:10.310 --> 00:01:13.387 align:middle line:90%
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:13.387 --> 00:01:14.220 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Hey, Nick.

00:01:14.220 --> 00:01:14.800 align:middle line:90%
Good to see you.

00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:15.540 align:middle line:90%
>> NICK BEGICH: Good to see you.

00:01:15.540 --> 00:01:15.970 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: You're looking well.

00:01:15.970 --> 00:01:17.261 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Thank you very much.

00:01:17.261 --> 00:01:17.960 align:middle line:90%
Good to see you.

00:01:17.960 --> 00:01:19.360 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: What's new with you?

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:20.930 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Just busy.

00:01:20.930 --> 00:01:22.260 align:middle line:90%
A lot of traveling these days.

00:01:22.260 --> 00:01:22.720 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Traveling.

00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:22.820 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Yeah.

00:01:22.820 --> 00:01:24.028 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Studying and stuff.

00:01:24.028 --> 00:01:27.020 align:middle line:84%
Well, as we will find out, you
study some very strange things.

00:01:27.020 --> 00:01:28.230 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Absolutely.

00:01:28.230 --> 00:01:32.340 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Nick, before we really
get going, as I introduced you,

00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:36.630 align:middle line:84%
the son of the late
congressman Nick Begich, Sr,

00:01:36.630 --> 00:01:38.510 align:middle line:84%
I know you don't like
to dwell on that,

00:01:38.510 --> 00:01:42.792 align:middle line:84%
but he died in a very tragic
episode with Hale Boggs.

00:01:42.792 --> 00:01:43.500 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Right.

00:01:43.500 --> 00:01:44.833 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Tell us what happened.

00:01:44.833 --> 00:01:47.630 align:middle line:84%
>> BEGICH: Well, he was
flying from Anchorage to Juno.

00:01:47.630 --> 00:01:49.192 align:middle line:84%
And it was a campaign
trip, actually.

00:01:49.192 --> 00:01:51.150 align:middle line:84%
Hale Boggs was the majority
leader at the time.

00:01:51.150 --> 00:01:55.194 align:middle line:84%
And it was just
before Watergate.

00:01:55.194 --> 00:01:56.860 align:middle line:84%
Boggs, the night
before in a fundraiser,

00:01:56.860 --> 00:01:59.200 align:middle line:84%
had just started talking
about this big thing

00:01:59.200 --> 00:02:00.740 align:middle line:90%
brewing in Washington.

00:02:00.740 --> 00:02:02.900 align:middle line:84%
Next morning, they flew
out on a small Cessna

00:02:02.900 --> 00:02:05.300 align:middle line:84%
and disappeared off
the radar screen

00:02:05.300 --> 00:02:07.281 align:middle line:84%
about 10 minutes
into the flight.

00:02:07.281 --> 00:02:09.030 align:middle line:84%
Biggest search in the
history of the world

00:02:09.030 --> 00:02:12.840 align:middle line:84%
at that time, and
absolutely nothing

00:02:12.840 --> 00:02:14.960 align:middle line:84%
was found after several
months of searching.

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:17.990 align:middle line:84%
And then I think it was
about 20 years later,

00:02:17.990 --> 00:02:22.719 align:middle line:84%
1993, where they actually ran
into some telexes from the FBI

00:02:22.719 --> 00:02:25.010 align:middle line:84%
indicating that they actually
did know where they were,

00:02:25.010 --> 00:02:26.340 align:middle line:90%
but they were never recovered.

00:02:26.340 --> 00:02:27.440 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Why not?

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:31.530 align:middle line:84%
>> BEGICH: Well, it was the
very end of the first time that

00:02:31.530 --> 00:02:32.570 align:middle line:90%
Nixon was in office.

00:02:32.570 --> 00:02:37.400 align:middle line:84%
And so his term was up, and he
was running for a second term.

00:02:37.400 --> 00:02:41.240 align:middle line:84%
Hale Boggs was a very,
very strong opponent

00:02:41.240 --> 00:02:42.890 align:middle line:84%
to what the FBI was
doing at the time.

00:02:42.890 --> 00:02:45.584 align:middle line:84%
There was a lot of pretty
shady things going on.

00:02:45.584 --> 00:02:47.750 align:middle line:84%
They were tapping all the
congressional phone lines.

00:02:47.750 --> 00:02:50.310 align:middle line:84%
They were interfering really
with the political process.

00:02:50.310 --> 00:02:55.450 align:middle line:84%
And so he was an enemy, if
you will, of the Nixon camp.

00:02:55.450 --> 00:02:56.429 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Who wasn't?

00:02:56.429 --> 00:02:57.470 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Yeah, exactly.

00:02:57.470 --> 00:02:59.370 align:middle line:84%
And it created a
lot of controversy.

00:02:59.370 --> 00:03:03.110 align:middle line:84%
And there were major issues
in Alaska time on land, oil

00:03:03.110 --> 00:03:05.730 align:middle line:84%
and gas, big minerals
issues on the table.

00:03:05.730 --> 00:03:07.550 align:middle line:84%
That really was the
root of it, I think,

00:03:07.550 --> 00:03:10.390 align:middle line:84%
and the fact that Boggs
wanted to reopen the Warren

00:03:10.390 --> 00:03:10.890 align:middle line:90%
Commission.

00:03:10.890 --> 00:03:12.090 align:middle line:90%
That was a big deal--

00:03:12.090 --> 00:03:12.140 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: It was huge.

00:03:12.140 --> 00:03:13.810 align:middle line:84%
>> BEGICH: --to reinvestigate
the Kennedy investigation.

00:03:13.810 --> 00:03:15.040 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Your brother's
now a US Senator.

00:03:15.040 --> 00:03:16.040 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: That's right.

00:03:16.040 --> 00:03:19.282 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: So the political life
runs in your blood, no doubt.

00:03:19.282 --> 00:03:19.990 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Right.

00:03:19.990 --> 00:03:22.930 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: At any point did your
family think somebody tampered

00:03:22.930 --> 00:03:24.280 align:middle line:90%
with this plane?

00:03:24.280 --> 00:03:26.150 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: That's come up.

00:03:26.150 --> 00:03:27.980 align:middle line:84%
But when those
telexes came out--

00:03:27.980 --> 00:03:31.680 align:middle line:84%
my mother had been involved in
politics up until that time--

00:03:31.680 --> 00:03:32.642 align:middle line:90%
she quit.

00:03:32.642 --> 00:03:33.600 align:middle line:90%
That was the end of it.

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:35.974 align:middle line:84%
And she felt that if this
could happen to a United States

00:03:35.974 --> 00:03:37.880 align:middle line:84%
Congressman, it
wasn't a government

00:03:37.880 --> 00:03:39.690 align:middle line:90%
that she wanted to serve in.

00:03:39.690 --> 00:03:41.990 align:middle line:84%
For the children, for
us, it was a motivator,

00:03:41.990 --> 00:03:45.441 align:middle line:84%
I think, to stay engaged,
to make the kind of changes

00:03:45.441 --> 00:03:46.940 align:middle line:84%
that need to be
made in the country.

00:03:46.940 --> 00:03:48.650 align:middle line:84%
And hopefully Mark
and the Senate

00:03:48.650 --> 00:03:50.310 align:middle line:84%
will do some things
that my father--

00:03:50.310 --> 00:03:51.310 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Let's hope so.

00:03:51.310 --> 00:03:52.897 align:middle line:84%
>> BEGICH: --would
have finished.

00:03:52.897 --> 00:03:55.230 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Has that episode,
regardless of what happened,

00:03:55.230 --> 00:04:00.096 align:middle line:84%
has that changed your
entire outlook and direction

00:04:00.096 --> 00:04:01.470 align:middle line:84%
for the career
that you've taken?

00:04:01.470 --> 00:04:03.565 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Oh, yeah.

00:04:03.565 --> 00:04:04.940 align:middle line:84%
When the plane
first disappeared,

00:04:04.940 --> 00:04:06.860 align:middle line:84%
it totally altered--
I was 14 years old.

00:04:06.860 --> 00:04:07.080 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Oh my gosh.

00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:08.000 align:middle line:84%
>> BEGICH: It
certainly altered--

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:09.400 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: And did you
understand what was going on?

00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:09.945 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Oh, absolutely.

00:04:09.945 --> 00:04:10.330 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: You did.

00:04:10.330 --> 00:04:12.590 align:middle line:84%
>> BEGICH: And it wasn't
the first time dad was down.

00:04:12.590 --> 00:04:17.010 align:middle line:84%
It's not an uncommon
situation in Alaska.

00:04:17.010 --> 00:04:18.630 align:middle line:90%
It was the Vietnam era, too.

00:04:18.630 --> 00:04:21.390 align:middle line:84%
A lot of my friends had
family members in Vietnam.

00:04:21.390 --> 00:04:23.012 align:middle line:84%
And it was similar
to what people

00:04:23.012 --> 00:04:24.720 align:middle line:84%
were experiencing with
missing in action.

00:04:24.720 --> 00:04:25.595 align:middle line:90%
You just didn't know.

00:04:25.595 --> 00:04:28.500 align:middle line:90%
You didn't have any finality.

00:04:28.500 --> 00:04:30.930 align:middle line:84%
Not having that finality,
as you grow older,

00:04:30.930 --> 00:04:32.180 align:middle line:90%
you kind of reconcile.

00:04:32.180 --> 00:04:35.732 align:middle line:84%
I think by the time I hit
my 30s, I finally did.

00:04:35.732 --> 00:04:37.190 align:middle line:84%
But no, I think it
was a motivator.

00:04:37.190 --> 00:04:38.615 align:middle line:84%
I'd always been
involved and my family

00:04:38.615 --> 00:04:40.406 align:middle line:84%
had always been involved
in public service.

00:04:40.406 --> 00:04:43.800 align:middle line:84%
That's the hallmark of what we
are in our region of the world.

00:04:43.800 --> 00:04:46.206 align:middle line:90%
And I think it was a motivator.

00:04:46.206 --> 00:04:47.580 align:middle line:84%
It certainly
changed my life, one

00:04:47.580 --> 00:04:51.920 align:middle line:84%
of the most horrible situations,
but at the same time one

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:53.900 align:middle line:84%
that absolutely I
can point to as being

00:04:53.900 --> 00:04:57.400 align:middle line:84%
a key element in making me
the person that I am today.

00:04:57.400 --> 00:05:01.266 align:middle line:84%
So as bad as it was, it had
that silver lining, if you will.

00:05:01.266 --> 00:05:03.640 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: And I've got to say,
knowing Nick as I have all

00:05:03.640 --> 00:05:05.557 align:middle line:84%
these years, you are a
remarkable human being.

00:05:05.557 --> 00:05:06.681 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Well, thank you.

00:05:06.681 --> 00:05:09.310 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: And we need about 10
million people like you on this

00:05:09.310 --> 00:05:11.840 align:middle line:84%
planet, spread out
all over the place.

00:05:11.840 --> 00:05:15.280 align:middle line:84%
You started getting
involved in looking

00:05:15.280 --> 00:05:19.950 align:middle line:84%
at the human mind and the
control of the human mind.

00:05:19.950 --> 00:05:22.220 align:middle line:84%
And I think you've
uncovered some things that

00:05:22.220 --> 00:05:26.400 align:middle line:84%
are very positive about that
control but also very dark.

00:05:26.400 --> 00:05:27.130 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Right.

00:05:27.130 --> 00:05:30.350 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Tell me about your
involvement in mind control.

00:05:30.350 --> 00:05:33.330 align:middle line:84%
>> BEGICH: Well, my interest
started really before I ever

00:05:33.330 --> 00:05:35.456 align:middle line:84%
started writing or did
any of the public work.

00:05:35.456 --> 00:05:36.830 align:middle line:84%
And I was very
interested in what

00:05:36.830 --> 00:05:40.820 align:middle line:84%
you could do to stimulate
the brain for meditation,

00:05:40.820 --> 00:05:43.770 align:middle line:84%
for accelerated learning, for
these kinds of applications.

00:05:43.770 --> 00:05:45.520 align:middle line:84%
When I ran into the
HAARP story, of course

00:05:45.520 --> 00:05:47.180 align:middle line:84%
there was that
component, the fact

00:05:47.180 --> 00:05:50.350 align:middle line:84%
that the signals that can be
generated from this device

00:05:50.350 --> 00:05:53.421 align:middle line:84%
could actually interfere
with brain function

00:05:53.421 --> 00:05:55.170 align:middle line:84%
in a way that was
pretty disturbing to me.

00:05:55.170 --> 00:05:58.480 align:middle line:84%
And that really got me to
start to look at this issue

00:05:58.480 --> 00:06:03.121 align:middle line:84%
more closely and also to advance
the issue into the public's

00:06:03.121 --> 00:06:03.620 align:middle line:90%
view.

00:06:03.620 --> 00:06:08.090 align:middle line:84%
And of course, Coast to Coast
and you and your predecessors

00:06:08.090 --> 00:06:10.930 align:middle line:84%
have been instrumental in
getting that issue out there.

00:06:10.930 --> 00:06:12.370 align:middle line:90%
So it's always been appreciated.

00:06:12.370 --> 00:06:16.580 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's changed a lot
of perspectives on what we can

00:06:16.580 --> 00:06:19.410 align:middle line:84%
do with the human mind
and has brought it

00:06:19.410 --> 00:06:23.510 align:middle line:84%
into the general
population as the dark side

00:06:23.510 --> 00:06:25.510 align:middle line:84%
and the bright side
of this technology.

00:06:25.510 --> 00:06:28.180 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Let's talk about some
of the things they're doing.

00:06:28.180 --> 00:06:30.320 align:middle line:84%
And who might they
be, by the way?

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:31.090 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Right.

00:06:31.090 --> 00:06:32.464 align:middle line:84%
DARPA's doing a
lot of this work.

00:06:32.464 --> 00:06:35.020 align:middle line:84%
And they do primarily research
for the various branches,

00:06:35.020 --> 00:06:35.960 align:middle line:90%
the military.

00:06:35.960 --> 00:06:38.580 align:middle line:84%
Going back even further, it was
Central Intelligence Agency,

00:06:38.580 --> 00:06:41.880 align:middle line:84%
which still has a great interest
in this type of technology.

00:06:41.880 --> 00:06:47.750 align:middle line:84%
The Navy has projects, Marines,
Air Force all have projects

00:06:47.750 --> 00:06:50.290 align:middle line:84%
in this area, all
under different names,

00:06:50.290 --> 00:06:51.780 align:middle line:90%
all under different programs.

00:06:51.780 --> 00:06:53.680 align:middle line:84%
But what we've
done over the years

00:06:53.680 --> 00:06:57.490 align:middle line:84%
is really compile the data
from the public record academic

00:06:57.490 --> 00:06:57.990 align:middle line:90%
records.

00:06:57.990 --> 00:07:00.370 align:middle line:84%
And you've got academic
institutions, of course,

00:07:00.370 --> 00:07:03.510 align:middle line:84%
heavily involved as
military contractors

00:07:03.510 --> 00:07:04.480 align:middle line:90%
in this kind of work.

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:08.590 align:middle line:84%
Most recently, DARPA
let two contracts, now

00:07:08.590 --> 00:07:10.015 align:middle line:84%
about a year, year
and a half ago,

00:07:10.015 --> 00:07:11.640 align:middle line:84%
to the University of
California to look

00:07:11.640 --> 00:07:14.410 align:middle line:84%
at electronic telepathy,
as an example.

00:07:14.410 --> 00:07:16.085 align:middle line:84%
So a lot of things
going on in the area,

00:07:16.085 --> 00:07:18.510 align:middle line:84%
and they continue to go on
for, essentially decades

00:07:18.510 --> 00:07:19.480 align:middle line:90%
this has been going on.

00:07:19.480 --> 00:07:22.030 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: What do they do to
try to control the human mind?

00:07:22.030 --> 00:07:26.050 align:middle line:84%
Because they're building,
I think, a force of people

00:07:26.050 --> 00:07:27.740 align:middle line:84%
to do some of these
strange things.

00:07:27.740 --> 00:07:28.725 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Right.

00:07:28.725 --> 00:07:33.000 align:middle line:84%
The original ideas actually go
back to the hypnotherapy labs

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.450 align:middle line:84%
at Harvard University
in the 1920s and '30s.

00:07:35.450 --> 00:07:37.850 align:middle line:84%
And a guy named
Estabrooks had come up

00:07:37.850 --> 00:07:40.710 align:middle line:84%
with this idea of creating
what we would call today

00:07:40.710 --> 00:07:43.200 align:middle line:84%
a Manchurian Candidate,
a sleeper, if you will,

00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:46.710 align:middle line:84%
someone that you could plant in
another country that would have

00:07:46.710 --> 00:07:49.560 align:middle line:84%
absolutely no recollection of
who they were but would act

00:07:49.560 --> 00:07:50.720 align:middle line:90%
as a super spy.

00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:52.560 align:middle line:84%
And that was his
general concept.

00:07:52.560 --> 00:07:55.790 align:middle line:84%
Now that idea advanced
into the '30s.

00:07:55.790 --> 00:07:59.020 align:middle line:84%
By the 1940s and
'50s, he was doing

00:07:59.020 --> 00:08:00.850 align:middle line:90%
classified work in this area.

00:08:00.850 --> 00:08:03.107 align:middle line:84%
By the '50s, right
after the Korean War,

00:08:03.107 --> 00:08:04.440 align:middle line:90%
is where the real interest came.

00:08:04.440 --> 00:08:06.830 align:middle line:84%
And that's when our
prisoners of war came back.

00:08:06.830 --> 00:08:08.850 align:middle line:84%
And these were patriotic
young men and women

00:08:08.850 --> 00:08:10.940 align:middle line:84%
that all of a sudden
they're handing out

00:08:10.940 --> 00:08:15.070 align:middle line:84%
communist leaflets on corners,
and the term brainwashing

00:08:15.070 --> 00:08:15.680 align:middle line:90%
was coined.

00:08:15.680 --> 00:08:18.430 align:middle line:84%
And that's kind of where
the CIA got real excited,

00:08:18.430 --> 00:08:21.624 align:middle line:84%
and then many projects started
to emerge at that point.

00:08:21.624 --> 00:08:23.790 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: There were some
who believe Sirhan Sirhan,

00:08:23.790 --> 00:08:26.510 align:middle line:84%
the convicted assassin
of Robert Kennedy,

00:08:26.510 --> 00:08:28.570 align:middle line:84%
might have been a
Manchurian Candidate.

00:08:28.570 --> 00:08:29.550 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Right.

00:08:29.550 --> 00:08:33.610 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: He originally
said that he had done it,

