>> NOORY: Noelle.

00:55:34.144 --> 00:55:35.352 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Thank you, Nicole.

00:55:35.352 --> 00:55:38.608 align:middle line:90%


00:55:38.608 --> 00:55:39.610 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:55:39.610 --> 00:55:43.890 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: That sound, how
can you hear it in the cheek?

00:55:43.890 --> 00:55:47.075 align:middle line:84%
Are we picking it up in the ear,
or it's going through our body?

00:55:47.075 --> 00:55:48.700 align:middle line:84%
>> BEGICH: It's going
through the body.

00:55:48.700 --> 00:55:50.158 align:middle line:84%
You can put it down
a little lower.

00:55:50.158 --> 00:55:51.816 align:middle line:90%
The signal gets a little weaker.

00:55:51.816 --> 00:55:54.634 align:middle line:84%
The power level on this is
about 60 volts peak to peak,

00:55:54.634 --> 00:55:56.050 align:middle line:84%
if you were to
look at the signal.

00:55:56.050 --> 00:55:58.410 align:middle line:84%
To get one that would transit,
say, through your feet,

00:55:58.410 --> 00:56:01.740 align:middle line:84%
you'd need about 3,000
volts peak to peak.

00:56:01.740 --> 00:56:03.440 align:middle line:84%
You're going to feel
a slight tingling,

00:56:03.440 --> 00:56:05.710 align:middle line:84%
but it's not going to be
like getting electrified,

00:56:05.710 --> 00:56:07.800 align:middle line:90%
because it's very low amperage.

00:56:07.800 --> 00:56:10.630 align:middle line:84%
But that creates a signal
that has a very quick rise

00:56:10.630 --> 00:56:12.680 align:middle line:90%
time and a very sharp spike.

00:56:12.680 --> 00:56:14.950 align:middle line:84%
So what it does is
every time it spikes

00:56:14.950 --> 00:56:18.680 align:middle line:84%
it creates a Radio
Frequency, RF, discharge that

00:56:18.680 --> 00:56:21.840 align:middle line:84%
then affects
cameras, microphones.

00:56:21.840 --> 00:56:24.640 align:middle line:84%
The earliest versions
that were produced of this

00:56:24.640 --> 00:56:27.770 align:middle line:84%
go back to the 1960s
by another inventor.

00:56:27.770 --> 00:56:29.260 align:middle line:90%
And he actually developed one.

00:56:29.260 --> 00:56:30.776 align:middle line:84%
This was before
microcircuits when

00:56:30.776 --> 00:56:32.150 align:middle line:84%
you could run this
kind of device

00:56:32.150 --> 00:56:33.233 align:middle line:90%
without that interference.

00:56:33.233 --> 00:56:36.180 align:middle line:90%
But the technology's advanced.

00:56:36.180 --> 00:56:39.650 align:middle line:84%
The idea that you can do this
wirelessly, the idea that you

00:56:39.650 --> 00:56:42.450 align:middle line:84%
can use other carriers
to embed a signal,

00:56:42.450 --> 00:56:44.500 align:middle line:84%
whether it's radio,
TV, internet,

00:56:44.500 --> 00:56:46.410 align:middle line:84%
that's where the
technology is today.

00:56:46.410 --> 00:56:51.300 align:middle line:84%
When you talk about sort of
where the info wars ultimately

00:56:51.300 --> 00:56:53.410 align:middle line:84%
target, it's going to be
hardware and software,

00:56:53.410 --> 00:56:54.985 align:middle line:90%
like we've all heard.

00:56:54.985 --> 00:56:56.610 align:middle line:84%
But it's also going
to be human beings.

00:56:56.610 --> 00:56:58.640 align:middle line:84%
Because, ultimately, if you
can shut down the human being,

00:56:58.640 --> 00:57:00.190 align:middle line:90%
the hardware doesn't matter.

00:57:00.190 --> 00:57:02.700 align:middle line:84%
And that's where that
technology is headed.

00:57:02.700 --> 00:57:04.960 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Are you are you
bullish on this technology?

00:57:04.960 --> 00:57:07.910 align:middle line:90%
Or are you afraid of it?

00:57:07.910 --> 00:57:10.330 align:middle line:84%
>> BEGICH: I'm excited about
the positive applications.

00:57:10.330 --> 00:57:12.280 align:middle line:84%
And this is, again, as
you bring those forward

00:57:12.280 --> 00:57:15.420 align:middle line:84%
and you move things
into the public domain,

00:57:15.420 --> 00:57:16.670 align:middle line:90%
it gets pretty exciting.

00:57:16.670 --> 00:57:19.450 align:middle line:84%
The wireless-type
technologies I'd

00:57:19.450 --> 00:57:21.700 align:middle line:84%
be a lot more cautious
on, because that's

00:57:21.700 --> 00:57:24.790 align:middle line:84%
where you are then
manipulating other people,

00:57:24.790 --> 00:57:26.330 align:middle line:84%
because the temptation
is too great.

00:57:26.330 --> 00:57:28.364 align:middle line:84%
Something that requires
a physical contact,

00:57:28.364 --> 00:57:29.780 align:middle line:84%
this is something
where people are

00:57:29.780 --> 00:57:30.505 align:middle line:90%
going to have a conversation.

00:57:30.505 --> 00:57:33.180 align:middle line:84%
You're not just going to show
up and put something on someone

00:57:33.180 --> 00:57:35.080 align:middle line:90%
without their consent.

00:57:35.080 --> 00:57:36.900 align:middle line:84%
So I think we need
to look at that.

00:57:36.900 --> 00:57:39.537 align:middle line:90%
We need to recognize the risks.

00:57:39.537 --> 00:57:40.620 align:middle line:90%
And then we need to limit.

00:57:40.620 --> 00:57:42.411 align:middle line:84%
Certain technologies
do need to be limited.

00:57:42.411 --> 00:57:45.510 align:middle line:84%
And perhaps on some ways
of carrying the signal,

00:57:45.510 --> 00:57:47.070 align:middle line:84%
we need to definitely
regulate that.

00:57:47.070 --> 00:57:50.110 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: But this could be
used for evil applications.

00:57:50.110 --> 00:57:51.250 align:middle line:90%
>> BEGICH: Absolutely.

00:57:51.250 --> 00:57:54.537 align:middle line:84%
The idea of accelerating
the learning

00:57:54.537 --> 00:57:55.495 align:middle line:90%
in the wrong direction.

00:57:55.495 --> 00:57:58.246 align:middle line:90%


00:57:58.246 --> 00:58:00.120 align:middle line:84%
One of the big things
with controlled effects

00:58:00.120 --> 00:58:01.578 align:middle line:84%
that the military
is looking for is

00:58:01.578 --> 00:58:03.150 align:middle line:84%
the idea of creating
memory sets.

00:58:03.150 --> 00:58:06.570 align:middle line:84%
In fact, "MIT Technology
Review" this month,

00:58:06.570 --> 00:58:08.220 align:middle line:84%
talking about people
who lose memory

00:58:08.220 --> 00:58:11.250 align:middle line:84%
and then being able to recreate
memory and give it to them.

00:58:11.250 --> 00:58:13.790 align:middle line:84%
Well, who's in control
of your memory?

00:58:13.790 --> 00:58:15.290 align:middle line:84%
And what do you
want to put in there

00:58:15.290 --> 00:58:17.850 align:middle line:84%
that now becomes your
sense of awareness?

00:58:17.850 --> 00:58:21.250 align:middle line:84%
And this is the problem is even
in educational applications,

00:58:21.250 --> 00:58:22.420 align:middle line:90%
which are coming.

00:58:22.420 --> 00:58:24.640 align:middle line:84%
The idea of who's doing
the programming-- when

00:58:24.640 --> 00:58:26.810 align:middle line:84%
you can take information,
literally download it

00:58:26.810 --> 00:58:29.140 align:middle line:84%
into a human brain, which
is where this technology one

00:58:29.140 --> 00:58:32.680 align:middle line:84%
day will be, who's going
to write the curriculum?

00:58:32.680 --> 00:58:34.820 align:middle line:84%
Who's going to set
the value judgments?

00:58:34.820 --> 00:58:36.970 align:middle line:84%
Who's going to make
those decisions?

00:58:36.970 --> 00:58:39.840 align:middle line:84%
What comes out of
this research in 10,

00:58:39.840 --> 00:58:43.470 align:middle line:84%
15 years is going to drive
educational institutions.

00:58:43.470 --> 00:58:45.630 align:middle line:84%
That's why we've got
to be involved now.

00:58:45.630 --> 00:58:48.170 align:middle line:84%
Because those outcomes
are much, much different.

00:58:48.170 --> 00:58:51.032 align:middle line:84%
PBS even did a thing that
says within 80 years--

00:58:51.032 --> 00:58:52.740 align:middle line:84%
and I think it's much
shorter than that--

00:58:52.740 --> 00:58:55.156 align:middle line:84%
that we'll have something
called the worldwide mind where,

00:58:55.156 --> 00:58:57.990 align:middle line:84%
like we link computers today,
we'll link consciousness then.

00:58:57.990 --> 00:58:59.270 align:middle line:90%
I think we already do that.

00:58:59.270 --> 00:59:00.480 align:middle line:90%
I think we do that naturally.

00:59:00.480 --> 00:59:01.880 align:middle line:90%
We're just not very aware of it.

00:59:01.880 --> 00:59:05.050 align:middle line:84%
But what we do naturally we're
trying to do synthetically

00:59:05.050 --> 00:59:07.240 align:middle line:84%
on a scale that would
be unprecedented.

00:59:07.240 --> 00:59:08.969 align:middle line:84%
And that's the direction
of the science.

00:59:08.969 --> 00:59:10.510 align:middle line:84%
That's where it goes
in the long run.

00:59:10.510 --> 00:59:13.300 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Well, and as you know,
sometimes in these movies you

00:59:13.300 --> 00:59:18.090 align:middle line:84%
